e appointed by the president without Senate confirmation.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Summary table - Number of czars per administration'''\n|-\n!President's name\n!Party\n!In office\n!Number of <br />czar titles\n!Number of <br />appointees\n!Appointees not <br />confirmed by Senate\n|-\n|Franklin Roosevelt\n|align=center |D\n|1933\u20131945\n|align=center |11\n|align=center |19\n|align=center |18\n|-\n|Harry Truman\n|align=center |D\n|1945\u20131953\n|align=center |6\n|align=center |6\n|align=center |5\n|-\n|Dwight Eisenhower\n|align=center |R\n|1953\u20131961\n|align=center |1\n|align=center |1\n|align=center |0\n|-\n|Lyndon Johnson\n|align=center |D\n|1963\u20131969\n|align=center |3\n|align=center |3\n|align=center |1\n|-\n|Richard Nixon\n|align=center |R\n|1969\u20131974\n|align=center |3\n|align=center |5\n|align=center |5\n|-\n|Gerald Ford\n|align=center |R\n|1974\u20131977\n|align=center |2\n|align=center |2\n|align=center |2\n|-\n|Jimmy Carter\n|align=center |D\n|1977\u20131981\n|align=center |2\n|align=center |3\n|align=center |2\n|-\n|Ronald Reagan\n|align=center |R\n|1981\u20131989\n|align=center |1\n|align=center |1\n|align=center |1\n|-\n|George H. W. Bush\n|align=center |R\n|1989\u20131993\n|align=center |2\n|align=center |3\n|align=center |0\n|-\n|Bill Clinton\n|align=center |D\n|1993\u20132001\n|align=center |8\n|align=center |11\n|align=center |7\n|-\n|George W. Bush\n|align=center |R\n|2001\u20132009\n|align=center |33\n|align=center |49\n|align=center |28\n|-\n|Barack Obama\n|align=center |D\n|2009\u20132017\n|align=center |38\n|align=center |50\n|align=center |39\n|-\n|Donald Trump\n|align=center |R\n|2017-\n|align=center |0 {{Update inline|date=July 2017}}\n|align=center |TBD {{Update inline|date=July 2017}}42\n|align=center |TBD {{Update inline|date=July 2017}}40\n|}\n\nThe numbers are based upon the sortable list below. Please see it for details and references.  Note that what is measured is the popularity of the ''word'' czar, rather than an objective measure of authority.\n\nAlso note that under George W. Bush only 33 Czar titles had been currently found, thus only 33 Czars, although many of these titles were used by several distinct individuals.  For example, there has been an Assistant Secretary of Labor for Mine Safety and Health since the passage of the [[Mine Safety and Health Act of 1977]], but the phrase \"mine safety czar\" was only applied to the position since the controversial appointment of [[Richard Stickler]] to the post in 2006.  Similarly, there has been a director of the [[Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs]] since the office was created by the [[Paperwork Reduction Act]] of 1980, but the term \"regulatory czar\" was not applied to the post until 2001.\n\n==List of executive branch czars==\nThe following are executive branch officials who have been described by the media as a czar of some kind.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Czar title\n! Official title\n! Office holder\n! Tenure\n! Type of appointment\n! Appointing administration\n! Senate confirmed\n|-\n|[[AfPak]] czar, Afghanistan and Pakistan czar\n|Special Representative for Afghanistan and Pakistan\n|[[Richard Holbrooke|Holbrooke, Richard]]<ref name=\"holbrookerichard\">Kondracke, Morton. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090512151541/http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2009/03/pakistan_must_be_obamas_leadin.html \"Pakistan Must Be Obama's Leading Foreign Priority\"], ''[[Roll Call]]'', Mar 13, 2009, archived by WebCite. Holland, Steve. [https://www.webcitation.org/5jquvIhG1?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSTRE54S5U120090529?pageNumber=2&virtualBrandChannel=0&sp=true \"Obama fashions a government of many czars\"], ''Reuters'', May 29, 2009, ''Archived by WebCite''.  {{sortname|Barack|Obama}}. [http://www.gpoaccess.gov/presdocs/2009/DCPD-200900196.htm \"Remarks on US Military and Diplomatic Strategies for Afghanistan and Pakistan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/2