{"title_page": "Henry Thomas Birch Reynardson", "text_new": "Lieutenant-Colonel '''Henry Thomas Birch Reynardson''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CMG}} (24 February 1892 \u2013 4 February 1972) was an officer in the Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry of the British Army.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=0Um-BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA434&dq=Lt-Col%20Henry%20Thomas%20Birch%20Reynardson&pg=PA434#v=onepage&q=Lt-Col%20Henry%20Thomas%20Birch%20Reynardson&f=false | title=History of the 43rd and 52nd (Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire) Light Infantry| isbn=9781781499511| date=2012-03-27}}</ref> He was the son of [[William John Birch Reynardson]] and married Diana Helen Ponsonby, daughter of the Hon. Edwin Charles William Ponsonby and Emily Dora Coope, on 14 September 1917.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birch Reynardson, Henry}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry officers]]\n[[Category:Birch Reynardson family]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n\n\n{{British-Army-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "Lt-Col '''Henry Thomas Birch Reynardson''' (24 February 1892 \u2013 4 February 1972) CMG was an officer in the Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry of the British Army.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=0Um-BAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA434&dq=Lt-Col%20Henry%20Thomas%20Birch%20Reynardson&pg=PA434#v=onepage&q=Lt-Col%20Henry%20Thomas%20Birch%20Reynardson&f=false | title=History of the 43rd and 52nd (Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire) Light Infantry| isbn=9781781499511| date=2012-03-27}}</ref> He was the son of [[William John Birch Reynardson]] and married Diana Helen Ponsonby, daughter of the Hon. Edwin Charles William Ponsonby and Emily Dora Coope, on 14 September 1917.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birch Reynardson, Henry}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry officers]]\n[[Category:Birch Reynardson family]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n\n\n{{British-Army-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Thomas_Birch_Reynardson"}
{"title_page": "Imam Suroso", "text_new": "{{short description|Indonesian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name = {{PAGENAME}}\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image = \n|imagesize = 220px\n|caption            =\n|office = Member of [[Dewan Perwakilan Rakyat|DPR RI]] Fraction [[PDIP]]\n|president = {{unbulleted list|[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]|[[Joko Widodo]]}}\n|term_start = 1 October 2009\n|term_end = 27 March 2020\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1964|1|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Pati Regency|Pati]], [[Central Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|27|1964|1|10}}\n|death_place = [[Semarang]], [[Central Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_cause = [[COVID-19]]\n|allegiance       = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|serviceyears     = 1987\u20142009\n|rank             = \n|branch           = [[Berkas:Insignia of the Indonesian National Police.svg|30px]] [[Kepolisian Negara Republik Indonesia]]\n|unit             = \n|awards           = \n|party            = [[Partai Demokrasi Indonesia Perjuangan]]\n|spouse           = Suhartini or Jeng Asih \n|children         = \n|residence        = \n|alma_mater       = {{unbulleted list|[[Universitas Bojonegoro]]|[[Universitas Bung Karno]]}}\n|occupation       = {{unbulleted list|[[Politician]]|[[Purnawirawan]] Polri|[[Humanist]]|[[Paranormal]]}}\n|religion         = [[Islam]]\n}}\n'''Imam Suroso''' (10 January 1964 - 27 March 2020) was an Indonesian politician who served as a member of the [[People's Representative Council|House of Representatives]] for three period, 2009\u20132014, 2014\u20132019 and 2019\u20132020<ref>[https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/28/pdi-p-lawmaker-passes-away-while-being-monitored-for-covid-19.html PDI-P lawmaker passes away while being monitored for COVID-19 - Politics - The Jakarta Post<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>. On 27 March 2020, he died while being monitored for COVID-19 - however, no actual cause of death was stated.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suroso, Imam}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indonesian politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Pati Regency]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia]]\n\n{{Indonesia-bio-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indonesian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name = {{PAGENAME}}\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image = \n|imagesize = 220px\n|caption            =\n|office = Member of [[Dewan Perwakilan Rakyat|DPR RI]] Fraction [[PDIP]]\n|president = {{unbulleted list|[[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]]|[[Joko Widodo]]}}\n|term_start = 1 October 2009\n|term_end = 27 March 2020\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1964|1|10}}\n|birth_place = [[Pati]], [[Central Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2020|3|27|1964|1|10}}\n|death_place = [[Semarang]], [[Central Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_cause = [[COVID-19]]\n|allegiance       = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|serviceyears     = 1987\u20142009\n|rank             = \n|branch           = [[Berkas:Insignia of the Indonesian National Police.svg|30px]] [[Kepolisian Negara Republik Indonesia]]\n|unit             = \n|awards           = \n|party            = [[Partai Demokrasi Indonesia Perjuangan]]\n|spouse           = Suhartini or Jeng Asih \n|children         = \n|residence        = \n|alma_mater       = {{unbulleted list|[[Universitas Bojonegoro]]|[[Universitas Bung Karno]]}}\n|occupation       = {{unbulleted list|[[Politician]]|[[Purnawirawan]] Polri|[[Humanist]]|[[Paranormal]]}}\n|religion         = [[Islam]]\n}}\n'''Imam Suroso''' (10 January 1964 - 27 March 2020) was an Indonesian politician who served as a member of the [[People's Representative Council|House of Representatives]] for three period, 2009\u20132014, 2014\u20132019 and 2019\u20132020<ref>[https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/28/pdi-p-lawmaker-passes-away-while-being-monitored-for-covid-19.html PDI-P lawmaker passes away while being monitored for COVID-19 - Politics - The Jakarta Post<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>. On 27 March 2020, he died while being monitored for COVID-19 - however, no actual cause of death was stated.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suroso, Imam}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indonesian politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Pati Regency]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia]]\n\n{{Indonesia-bio-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPati(link changed toPati Regency) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imam_Suroso"}
{"title_page": "Ecology Center (Ann Arbor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Ecology Center\n| logo   = EClogo stacked color-01.png\n| type   = [[501(c)3]]\n| founded_date      = 1970<br/>[[Ann Arbor, MI]], United States\n| location          = [[Ann Arbor, MI]], United States\n| key_people        = Mike Garfield, Director\n| focus             = [[Environmentalism]], [[Global warming|Global Warming]], [[Renewable Energy]]\n| method            = [[Direct action]], [[lobbying]], [[petition]], [[Demonstration (people)|demonstration]]\n| homepage          = ecocenter.org [http://ecocenter.org/]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ecology Center''' is a membership-based nonprofit [[environmental organization]] based in [[Ann Arbor]], [[Michigan]]. It works at the local, state and national levels on [[environmental justice]], health, waste, and community issues. \nIt was formed after the first [[Earth Day]] in 1970 by community activists in [[Ann Arbor]]. Since its founding, it has run demonstrations and campaigns to promote recycling, health care, education, and awareness about healthy foods and products.<ref>Juliana Keeping \"Ecology Center turns 40, celebrates milestone with talk by environmental activist Van Jones\" AnnArbor.com [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ecology-center-turns-40/]</ref>\n\n==Vision==\nThe vision of the Ecology Center is a world of healthy people living in harmony with the natural world.  We promote clean industries making non-toxic, waste-free, bio-based products for a world fueled by clean energy, fed by local organic food, and housed in communities that enhance the natural world\u2019s biological diversity.\n\n==History==\nAfter the first Earth Day in 1970, community activists in Ann Arbor formed the Ecology Center to promote safe and healthy environments for people. Among their demonstrations and projects the group created a recycling program which have since grown into a wholly owned green business. \nIn the 1990s, the Ecology Center created one of the largest land preservation programs in the country. As of 2010 more than 8,000 acres of farms and natural areas in southeast Michigan have been protected.<ref>Juliana Keeping \"Ecology Center turns 40, celebrates milestone with talk by environmental activist Van Jones\" [[AnnArbor.com]] [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ecology-center-turns-40/]</ref>\n\nThe Ecology Center led a statewide campaign that closed every single one of Michigan\u2019s 157 [[medical waste]] incinerators\u2014the second leading source of mercury and dioxin emissions into the environment.\n\nA coalition led by the Ecology Center won federal mandates to remove lead and recover mercury from vehicles in the United States.\n\nBeginning in 2005, the Ecology Center developed a unique resource, HealthyStuff.org that tests common products for lead, mercury, or other toxic chemicals.\n\nIn 2011, the Ecology Center was named a \"Green Leader\" by the [[Detroit Free Press]]. The award recognizes \"individuals, businesses and organizations who exhibit excellence in environmental responsibility.\"\n\nIn July 2011, the Ecology Center moved into an expanded office at 339 E. Liberty, Ann Arbor, known as the Handicraft Building. In keeping with the Ecology Center's mission, the new office space incorporated many green features, including sustainable and recycled materials.\n<ref>AnnArbor.com, \"Ann Arbor Ecology Center moving to new home in downtown Ann Arbor\", April 23, 2011 [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ann-arbor-ecology-center-moving-to-new-home-in-downtown-ann-arbor]</ref>  Students from Eastern Michigan University designed furniture for the office using reclaimed materials.<ref>Ann Arbor.com, \"Hands-on experience: EMU students design workspaces for new Ecology Center offices\", December 27, 2011 [http://www.annarbor.com/news/emu-designs-furniture-for-new-ecology-center-offices]</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n\n===Climate & Energy===\nThe Ecology Center's Clean Energy, Clean Fuels Campaign promotes policy solutions that increase United States energy independence, decrease Michigan's global warming pollution, and encourage sustainable agricultural and forestry practices that improve soil quality, enhance wildlife habitat, and preserve other conservation values\n\n===Environmental Education===\nThe Ecology Center brings hands-on environmental lessons to schools throughout southeastern Michigan.  Programs include classroom visits, teacher training and curriculum development and web links and printed resources for teachers.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/education/environmental-education |title=Ecology Center website \"Environmental education\" |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106072944/http://www.ecocenter.org/education/environmental-education |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Michigan Network for Children's Environmental Health===\nThe Ecology Center is a member of the [http://www.mnceh.org Michigan Network for Children's Environmental Health] which aims to promote healthy and safe environment for children through advocacy, education, outreach, and cooperation with health professionals, health affected groups, and environmental organizations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/safe-kids-homes-towns/safe-kids-homes-towns |title=Ecology Center website \"Safe Kids Homes Towns\" |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106074717/http://www.ecocenter.org/safe-kids-homes-towns/safe-kids-homes-towns |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===HealthyStuff===\nA website launched by the Ecology Center, HealthyStuff offers a listing the amount of lead, arsenic, mercury, chlorine, and bromine in over 900 products including toys, school supplies, car seats, automobiles, pet products, apparels, and home improvement tools and supplies. \n<ref>[http://www.healthystuff.org/ www.healthystuff.org]</ref>\n\n===Land Use===\nThe goal is to preserve farmland and natural areas, concentrate development where infrastructure exists, and reduce traffic congestion.\n\n===Recycle Ann Arbor===\nFounded in 1977, Recycle Ann Arbor is a nonprofit organization that grew out of the Ecology Center recycling program. It is Michigan\u2019s first curbside recycling program in 1978 and currently operates dropoff stations and reused building material and  household supply shops for Ann Arbor residents.<ref>[http://www.recycleannarbor.org Recycle Ann Arbor website]</ref>\nSee also [[Energy Works Michigan]] <ref>[http://www.recycleannarbor.org/?module=Page&sID=about-recycle-ann-arbor  Recycle Ann Arbor \"About Us\"]</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n===[[Healthy Food in Health Care]]===\nThe ecology center works with hospitals across Michigan to provide locally and sustainably produced foods for their patients and staff. To date over 300 hospitals across the nation have signed on.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwonline.squarespace.com/storage/journal-issue-47/ecology%20center%20web%2047.pdf |title=Bill Zirinsky \"Bringing Healthy Foods into Michigan\u2019s Hospitals\" |access-date=2011-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814045606/http://cwonline.squarespace.com/storage/journal-issue-47/ecology%20center%20web%2047.pdf |archive-date=2011-08-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===[[Green Chemistry]]===\nGreen chemistry is a scientific movement aimed at replacing toxic chemicals with safer alternatives. The Ecology Center has been involved in the movement shortly after its founding and received a Green Chemistry Gubernatorial Awards in 2009 by the state governor. \n<ref>[http://www.ecocenter.org/newsletter/ecolink/feb11/article-green-chemistry.php Ecolink]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===[[Built by Michigan]]===\nThe Built By Michigan coalition brings together small business, large business, workers, families, electric vehicle owners and car aficionados, environmental and faith based organizations, and more to advance the manufacturing and sales of the electric vehicle in Michigan to strengthen the local economy and increase employment in the state.\n<ref>[http://progressmichigan.pnstate.org/site/PageNavigator/ElectricVehicles.html Built by Michigan]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===[[Energy Works Michigan]]===\nEnergy Works Michigan is a non-profit technical resource building foundational capacities for a sustainable, equitable, and prosperous future in Michigan. \n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.energyworksmichigan.org/about-us |title=Energy Works Michigan About Us |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322230215/http://www.energyworksmichigan.org/about-us |archive-date=2012-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===[[Save Land, Build Community]]===\nThe Ecology Center helps local communities develop additional tools for preservation \u2014 in particular, local funding to buy land or development rights from willing sellers. Since 2000, the Ecology Center has led or co-organized five separate successful land preservation ballot campaigns in the Ann Arbor area, raising over $100 million that\u2019s projected to save over 10,000 acres of working farms and natural areas. We\u2019ve also helped bring together community leaders to discuss regional solutions to regional land use problems.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/save-land-build-community/save-land-build-community |title=Save Land |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106082851/http://www.ecocenter.org/save-land-build-community/save-land-build-community |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ecocenter.org/] Ecology Center Website\n* [http://HealthyStuff.org/] HealthyStuff website\n* [http://recycleannarbor.org/] Recycle Ann Arbor\n\n[[Category:Climate change organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Youth empowerment organizations]]\n[[Category:Youth-led organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Ecology Center\n| logo   = EClogo stacked color-01.png\n| type   = [[501(c)3]]\n| founded_date      = 1970<br/>[[Ann Arbor, MI]], United States\n| location          = [[Ann Arbor, MI]], United States\n| key_people        = Mike Garfield, Director\n| focus             = [[Environmentalism]], [[Global Warming]], [[Renewable Energy]]\n| method            = [[Direct action]], [[lobbying]], [[petition]], [[Demonstration (people)|demonstration]]\n| homepage          = ecocenter.org [http://ecocenter.org/]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ecology Center''' is a membership-based nonprofit [[environmental organization]] based in [[Ann Arbor]], [[Michigan]]. It works at the local, state and national levels on [[environmental justice]], health, waste, and community issues. \nIt was formed after the first [[Earth Day]] in 1970 by community activists in [[Ann Arbor]]. Since its founding, it has run demonstrations and campaigns to promote recycling, health care, education, and awareness about healthy foods and products.<ref>Juliana Keeping \"Ecology Center turns 40, celebrates milestone with talk by environmental activist Van Jones\" AnnArbor.com [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ecology-center-turns-40/]</ref>\n\n==Vision==\nThe vision of the Ecology Center is a world of healthy people living in harmony with the natural world.  We promote clean industries making non-toxic, waste-free, bio-based products for a world fueled by clean energy, fed by local organic food, and housed in communities that enhance the natural world\u2019s biological diversity.\n\n==History==\nAfter the first Earth Day in 1970, community activists in Ann Arbor formed the Ecology Center to promote safe and healthy environments for people. Among their demonstrations and projects the group created a recycling program which have since grown into a wholly owned green business. \nIn the 1990s, the Ecology Center created one of the largest land preservation programs in the country. As of 2010 more than 8,000 acres of farms and natural areas in southeast Michigan have been protected.<ref>Juliana Keeping \"Ecology Center turns 40, celebrates milestone with talk by environmental activist Van Jones\" [[AnnArbor.com]] [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ecology-center-turns-40/]</ref>\n\nThe Ecology Center led a statewide campaign that closed every single one of Michigan\u2019s 157 [[medical waste]] incinerators\u2014the second leading source of mercury and dioxin emissions into the environment.\n\nA coalition led by the Ecology Center won federal mandates to remove lead and recover mercury from vehicles in the United States.\n\nBeginning in 2005, the Ecology Center developed a unique resource, HealthyStuff.org that tests common products for lead, mercury, or other toxic chemicals.\n\nIn 2011, the Ecology Center was named a \"Green Leader\" by the [[Detroit Free Press]]. The award recognizes \"individuals, businesses and organizations who exhibit excellence in environmental responsibility.\"\n\nIn July 2011, the Ecology Center moved into an expanded office at 339 E. Liberty, Ann Arbor, known as the Handicraft Building. In keeping with the Ecology Center's mission, the new office space incorporated many green features, including sustainable and recycled materials.\n<ref>AnnArbor.com, \"Ann Arbor Ecology Center moving to new home in downtown Ann Arbor\", April 23, 2011 [http://www.annarbor.com/news/ann-arbor-ecology-center-moving-to-new-home-in-downtown-ann-arbor]</ref>  Students from Eastern Michigan University designed furniture for the office using reclaimed materials.<ref>Ann Arbor.com, \"Hands-on experience: EMU students design workspaces for new Ecology Center offices\", December 27, 2011 [http://www.annarbor.com/news/emu-designs-furniture-for-new-ecology-center-offices]</ref>\n\n==Programs==\n\n===Climate & Energy===\nThe Ecology Center's Clean Energy, Clean Fuels Campaign promotes policy solutions that increase United States energy independence, decrease Michigan's global warming pollution, and encourage sustainable agricultural and forestry practices that improve soil quality, enhance wildlife habitat, and preserve other conservation values\n\n===Environmental Education===\nThe Ecology Center brings hands-on environmental lessons to schools throughout southeastern Michigan.  Programs include classroom visits, teacher training and curriculum development and web links and printed resources for teachers.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/education/environmental-education |title=Ecology Center website \"Environmental education\" |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106072944/http://www.ecocenter.org/education/environmental-education |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Michigan Network for Children's Environmental Health===\nThe Ecology Center is a member of the [http://www.mnceh.org Michigan Network for Children's Environmental Health] which aims to promote healthy and safe environment for children through advocacy, education, outreach, and cooperation with health professionals, health affected groups, and environmental organizations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/safe-kids-homes-towns/safe-kids-homes-towns |title=Ecology Center website \"Safe Kids Homes Towns\" |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106074717/http://www.ecocenter.org/safe-kids-homes-towns/safe-kids-homes-towns |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===HealthyStuff===\nA website launched by the Ecology Center, HealthyStuff offers a listing the amount of lead, arsenic, mercury, chlorine, and bromine in over 900 products including toys, school supplies, car seats, automobiles, pet products, apparels, and home improvement tools and supplies. \n<ref>[http://www.healthystuff.org/ www.healthystuff.org]</ref>\n\n===Land Use===\nThe goal is to preserve farmland and natural areas, concentrate development where infrastructure exists, and reduce traffic congestion.\n\n===Recycle Ann Arbor===\nFounded in 1977, Recycle Ann Arbor is a nonprofit organization that grew out of the Ecology Center recycling program. It is Michigan\u2019s first curbside recycling program in 1978 and currently operates dropoff stations and reused building material and  household supply shops for Ann Arbor residents.<ref>[http://www.recycleannarbor.org Recycle Ann Arbor website]</ref>\nSee also [[Energy Works Michigan]] <ref>[http://www.recycleannarbor.org/?module=Page&sID=about-recycle-ann-arbor  Recycle Ann Arbor \"About Us\"]</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\n\n===[[Healthy Food in Health Care]]===\nThe ecology center works with hospitals across Michigan to provide locally and sustainably produced foods for their patients and staff. To date over 300 hospitals across the nation have signed on.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwonline.squarespace.com/storage/journal-issue-47/ecology%20center%20web%2047.pdf |title=Bill Zirinsky \"Bringing Healthy Foods into Michigan\u2019s Hospitals\" |access-date=2011-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814045606/http://cwonline.squarespace.com/storage/journal-issue-47/ecology%20center%20web%2047.pdf |archive-date=2011-08-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===[[Green Chemistry]]===\nGreen chemistry is a scientific movement aimed at replacing toxic chemicals with safer alternatives. The Ecology Center has been involved in the movement shortly after its founding and received a Green Chemistry Gubernatorial Awards in 2009 by the state governor. \n<ref>[http://www.ecocenter.org/newsletter/ecolink/feb11/article-green-chemistry.php Ecolink]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===[[Built by Michigan]]===\nThe Built By Michigan coalition brings together small business, large business, workers, families, electric vehicle owners and car aficionados, environmental and faith based organizations, and more to advance the manufacturing and sales of the electric vehicle in Michigan to strengthen the local economy and increase employment in the state.\n<ref>[http://progressmichigan.pnstate.org/site/PageNavigator/ElectricVehicles.html Built by Michigan]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===[[Energy Works Michigan]]===\nEnergy Works Michigan is a non-profit technical resource building foundational capacities for a sustainable, equitable, and prosperous future in Michigan. \n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.energyworksmichigan.org/about-us |title=Energy Works Michigan About Us |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322230215/http://www.energyworksmichigan.org/about-us |archive-date=2012-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===[[Save Land, Build Community]]===\nThe Ecology Center helps local communities develop additional tools for preservation \u2014 in particular, local funding to buy land or development rights from willing sellers. Since 2000, the Ecology Center has led or co-organized five separate successful land preservation ballot campaigns in the Ann Arbor area, raising over $100 million that\u2019s projected to save over 10,000 acres of working farms and natural areas. We\u2019ve also helped bring together community leaders to discuss regional solutions to regional land use problems.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecocenter.org/save-land-build-community/save-land-build-community |title=Save Land |access-date=2012-01-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106082851/http://www.ecocenter.org/save-land-build-community/save-land-build-community |archive-date=2012-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ecocenter.org/] Ecology Center Website\n* [http://HealthyStuff.org/] HealthyStuff website\n* [http://recycleannarbor.org/] Recycle Ann Arbor\n\n[[Category:Climate change organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Youth empowerment organizations]]\n[[Category:Youth-led organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGlobal warming (disambiguation)(link changed toGlobal warming) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ecology_Center_(Ann_Arbor)"}
{"title_page": "The Brass Are Comin'", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Brass Are Comin'\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Herb Alpert|Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1969\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[instrumental pop, easy listening]]\n| length     = 33:35\n| label      = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| producer   = [[Herb Alpert]], [[Jerry Moss]]\n| prev_title = [[Warm (Herb Alpert album)|Warm]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Greatest Hits (Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n'''''The Brass Are Comin'''''' is a 1969 album by [[Herb Alpert]] & the Tijuana Brass. It was the group's thirteenth release and marked the first time in the group's history that one of their albums did not certify gold.  However, the album did peak at number 30 in the top 40 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' albums chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Brass Are Comin'|url=http://www.tijuanabrass.com/tjb2.php3|website=Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass Discography|accessdate=June 28, 2005}}</ref>  ''The Brass Are Comin''' was the last album recorded by the Tijuana Brass before the group disbanded in December 1969.  The album also spawned a television special with the same name that aired on [[NBC]] on October 29, 1969.  <ref>{{cite journal|title=Television October 31, 1969|journal=Time|date=October 31, 1969|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,839081,00.html|accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>  Clips from the television special can be seen on the album's double-fold cover.  Unlike the previous [[Warm (Herb Alpert album)|Warm]] album which featured much slower-paced songs leaning more toward a \"Brazilian\" sound, The Brass Are Comin' featured a western-theme with faster-paced songs.  \"Good Morning, Mr. Sunshine\" became one of the most recognized Tijuana Brass songs from this album and was among the last Mexican-flavored songs recorded by the group <ref>{{cite web|title=The Brass Are Comin'|url=http://www.tijuanabrass.com/tjb2.php3|website=Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass Discography|accessdate=June 28, 2005}}</ref>.  After completing this album and the subsequent television special, the group embarked on a European tour which marked the last public performances of the original TJB. <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Oney|first1=Steve|title=Herb Alpert:  Always In Tune|journal=Los Angeles Magazine|date=May 1, 2011|url=http://www.lamag.com/longform/herb-alpert-always-in-tune-11/}}</ref> \n\n==Track listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Track\n!Title\n!Composers\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|The Brass Are Comin' (The Little Train of Caipra)\n|Villa Lobos\n|2:06\n|-\n|2\n|Good Morning, Mr. Sunshine\n|Alexander F. Roth, Irving Mills\n|2:36\n|-\n|3\n|Country Lake\n|Sol Lake\n|2:56\n|-\n|4\n|I'll Be Back\n|John Lennon, Paul McCartney\n|3:15\n|-\n|5\n|Moon River\n|Henry Mancini, Johnny Mercer\n|2:55\n|-\n|6\n|The Maltese Melody\n|Bert Kaempfert, Herbert Rehbein\n|2:13\n|-\n|7\n|Sunny\n|Bobby Hebb\n|3:11\n|-\n|8\n|I'm An Old Cowhand (From the Rio Grande)\n|Johnny Mercer\n|2:38\n|-\n|9\n|Anna\n|F. Giordano, R. Vatro, William Engvick\n|2:39\n|-\n|10\n|Robbers and Cops\n|Julius Wechter\n|2:13\n|-\n|11\n|Moments\n|John Pisano\n|2:43\n|-\n|12\n|You Are My Life\n|Peter Sarsedt\n|3:23\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*All information from album labels from ''The Brass Are Comin''' released in 1969 by A&M Records, SP-4228.\n\n{{Herb Alpert}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brass Are Comin}}\n[[Category:1969 albums]]\n[[Category:Herb Alpert albums]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Herb Alpert]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Jerry Moss]]\n[[Category:A&M Records albums]]\n\n{{1960s-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Brass Are Comin'\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Herb Alpert|Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1969\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 33:54\n| label      = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| producer   = [[Herb Alpert]], [[Jerry Moss]]\n| prev_title = [[Warm (Herb Alpert album)|Warm]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Greatest Hits (Herb Alpert and the Tijuana Brass album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n'''''The Brass Are Comin'''''' is a 1969 album by [[Herb Alpert]] & the Tijuana Brass. It was the group's thirteenth release and marked the first time in the group's history that one of their albums did not certify gold.  However, the album did peak at number 30 in the top 40 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' albums chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Brass Are Comin'|url=http://www.tijuanabrass.com/tjb2.php3|website=Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass Discography|accessdate=June 28, 2005}}</ref>  ''The Brass Are Comin''' was the last album recorded by the Tijuana Brass before the group disbanded in December 1969.  The album also spawned a television special with the same name that aired on [[NBC]] on October 29, 1969.  <ref>{{cite journal|title=Television October 31, 1969|journal=Time|date=October 31, 1969|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,839081,00.html|accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>  Clips from the television special can be seen on the album's double-fold cover.  Unlike the previous [[Warm (Herb Alpert album)|Warm]] album which featured much slower-paced songs leaning more toward a \"Brazilian\" sound, The Brass Are Comin' featured a western-theme with faster-paced songs.  \"Good Morning, Mr. Sunshine\" became one of the most recognized Tijuana Brass songs from this album and was among the last Mexican-flavored songs recorded by the group <ref>{{cite web|title=The Brass Are Comin'|url=http://www.tijuanabrass.com/tjb2.php3|website=Herb Alpert & the Tijuana Brass Discography|accessdate=June 28, 2005}}</ref>.  After completing this album and the subsequent television special, the group embarked on a European tour which marked the last public performances of the original TJB. <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Oney|first1=Steve|title=Herb Alpert:  Always In Tune|journal=Los Angeles Magazine|date=May 1, 2011|url=http://www.lamag.com/longform/herb-alpert-always-in-tune-11/}}</ref> \n\n==Track listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Track\n!Title\n!Composers\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|The Brass Are Comin' (The Little Train of Caipra)\n|Villa Lobos\n|2:06\n|-\n|2\n|Good Morning, Mr. Sunshine\n|Alexander F. Roth, Irving Mills\n|2:36\n|-\n|3\n|Country Lake\n|Sol Lake\n|2:56\n|-\n|4\n|I'll Be Back\n|John Lennon, Paul McCartney\n|3:15\n|-\n|5\n|Moon River\n|Henry Mancini, Johnny Mercer\n|2:55\n|-\n|6\n|The Maltese Melody\n|Bert Kaempfert, Herbert Rehbein\n|2:13\n|-\n|7\n|Sunny\n|Bobby Hebb\n|3:11\n|-\n|8\n|I'm An Old Cowhand (From the Rio Grande)\n|Johnny Mercer\n|2:38\n|-\n|9\n|Anna\n|F. Giordano, R. Vatro, William Engvick\n|2:39\n|-\n|10\n|Robbers and Cops\n|Julius Wechter\n|2:13\n|-\n|11\n|Moments\n|John Pisano\n|2:43\n|-\n|12\n|You Are My Life\n|Peter Sarsedt\n|3:23\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*All information from album labels from ''The Brass Are Comin''' released in 1969 by A&M Records, SP-4228.\n\n{{Herb Alpert}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brass Are Comin}}\n[[Category:1969 albums]]\n[[Category:Herb Alpert albums]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Herb Alpert]]\n[[Category:albums produced by Jerry Moss]]\n[[Category:A&M Records albums]]\n\n{{1960s-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Artur Sienkiewicz", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed genre and total time", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Brass_Are_Comin%27"}
{"title_page": "Limulus", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n|fossil_range = {{fossil range|244|0}}\n|image = L polyphemus L darwini.png\n|image_caption = Modern ''L. polyphemus'' compared to the very similar Jurassic ''L. darwini''\n|taxon = Limulus\n|authority = [[Otto Friedrich M\u00fcller|O. F. M\u00fcller]], 1785\n|type_species = ''[[Limulus polyphemus]]''\n|type_species_authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n|synonyms = * ''Xiphosura''\n}}\n\n'''''Limulus''''' is a genus of [[horseshoe crab]], with one extinct species, the [[Atlantic horseshoe crab]] (''Limulus polyphemus'').  Many fossil species are known, many of which have since been assigned to other genera.<ref name=\"Pleaseexpand\">{{cite journal | last1 = S. | first1 = Leif  | year = 1952 | title = Phylogeny and Taxonomy of Fossil Horseshoe Crabs | journal = Journal of Paleontology | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 630\u2013640 | publisher = SEPM Society for Sedimentary Geology | jstor = 1299851}}</ref>\n\nCurrently valid species include:<ref name=fossils>Dunlop, J. A., Penney, D. & Jekel, D. 2013. A summary list of fossil spiders and their relatives. In Platnick, N. I. (ed.) ''The world spider catalog, version 14.0'' American Museum of Natural History, online at http://research.amnh.org/entomology/spiders/catalog/index.html</ref>\n*''[[Limulus polyphemus]]'' <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small>\n*''[[Limulus coffini]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Reeside & Harris, 1952</small>- [[Cretaceous]], [[United States]]\n*''Limulus darwini''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Kin & B\u0142a\u017cejowski, 2014</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[Poland]]<ref name=K&B2014>{{cite journal|last1=Kin|first1=Adrian|last2=B\u0142a\u017cejowski|first2=B\u0142a\u017cej|title=The Horseshoe Crab of the Genus ''Limulus'': Living Fossil or Stabilomorph?|journal=PLoS ONE|date=2014|volume=9|issue=10|pages=e108036|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0108036|url=http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0108036|pmid=25275563|pmc=4183490}}</ref>\n*''[[Limulus priscus]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>M\u00fcnster, 1839</small>- [[Triassic]], [[Germany]]\n*''[[Limulus woodwardi]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Watson, 1909</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[England]]\n\nDoubtful species include:<ref name=fossils/>\n* ''[[Limulus nathorsti]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Jackson, 1906</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[Sweden]]\n\nTentative species:<ref name=fossils/>\n*''\"[[Limulus\" decheni]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Zinken, 1862</small>- [[Paleogene]], [[Germany]] (considered by some intermediate between ''Limulus'' and ''[[Tachypleus]]'')<ref name=fossils/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2104567}}\n\n[[Category:Xiphosura]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric chelicerates]]\n[[Category:Monotypic arthropod genera]]\n[[Category:Extant Triassic first appearances]]\n\n\n{{paleo-arthropod-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n|fossil_range = {{fossil range|244|0}}\n|image = L polyphemus L darwini.png\n|image_caption = Modern ''L. polyphemus'' compared to the very similar Jurassic ''L. darwini''\n|taxon = Limulus\n|authority = [[Otto Friedrich M\u00fcller|O. F. M\u00fcller]], 1785\n|type_species = ''[[Limulus polyphemus]]''\n|type_species_authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n|synonyms = * ''Xiphosura''\n}}\n\n'''''Limulus''''' is a genus of [[horseshoe crab]], with one extant species, the [[Atlantic horseshoe crab]] (''Limulus polyphemus'').  Many fossil species are known, many of which have since been assigned to other genera.<ref name=\"Pleaseexpand\">{{cite journal | last1 = S. | first1 = Leif  | year = 1952 | title = Phylogeny and Taxonomy of Fossil Horseshoe Crabs | journal = Journal of Paleontology | volume = 26 | issue = 4 | pages = 630\u2013640 | publisher = SEPM Society for Sedimentary Geology | jstor = 1299851}}</ref>\n\nCurrently valid species include:<ref name=fossils>Dunlop, J. A., Penney, D. & Jekel, D. 2013. A summary list of fossil spiders and their relatives. In Platnick, N. I. (ed.) ''The world spider catalog, version 14.0'' American Museum of Natural History, online at http://research.amnh.org/entomology/spiders/catalog/index.html</ref>\n*''[[Limulus polyphemus]]'' <small>([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])</small>\n*''[[Limulus coffini]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Reeside & Harris, 1952</small>- [[Cretaceous]], [[United States]]\n*''Limulus darwini''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Kin & B\u0142a\u017cejowski, 2014</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[Poland]]<ref name=K&B2014>{{cite journal|last1=Kin|first1=Adrian|last2=B\u0142a\u017cejowski|first2=B\u0142a\u017cej|title=The Horseshoe Crab of the Genus ''Limulus'': Living Fossil or Stabilomorph?|journal=PLoS ONE|date=2014|volume=9|issue=10|pages=e108036|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0108036|url=http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0108036|pmid=25275563|pmc=4183490}}</ref>\n*''[[Limulus priscus]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>M\u00fcnster, 1839</small>- [[Triassic]], [[Germany]]\n*''[[Limulus woodwardi]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Watson, 1909</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[England]]\n\nDoubtful species include:<ref name=fossils/>\n* ''[[Limulus nathorsti]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Jackson, 1906</small>- [[Jurassic]], [[Sweden]]\n\nTentative species:<ref name=fossils/>\n*''\"[[Limulus\" decheni]]''[[extinction|\u2020]] <small>Zinken, 1862</small>- [[Paleogene]], [[Germany]] (considered by some intermediate between ''Limulus'' and ''[[Tachypleus]]'')<ref name=fossils/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2104567}}\n\n[[Category:Xiphosura]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric chelicerates]]\n[[Category:Monotypic arthropod genera]]\n[[Category:Extant Triassic first appearances]]\n\n\n{{paleo-arthropod-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aneeshtantric", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limulus"}
